Now up to seven sacks on the season, Burns should be counted as a DL1 option for Week 15 despite the neutral matchup against the Baltimore Ravens. Back on the sack ledger after a two week gap since recording at least one sack in six of eight games, Burns should be rostered and started universally, regardless of provider.

Wonnum was solid in Week 14, tallying three solos, two assists, and one sack. Wonnum has recorded a sack in three of his four games since making his Panthers debut and should be considered a strong DL2 option for Week 15, thanks to a tasty matchup against the Dallas Cowboys. Start Wonnum where needed.

Heyward was excellent in Week 14, tallying three solos, two assists, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. Heyward has three sacks in his last two games and five in his last five. Now up to eight sacks on the season, Cam is safe to deploy as a DT1/DL2 for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Philadelphia Eagles.

A'Shawn continues to impress for the Carolina Panthers, most recently tallying two solos, three assists, 1.5 sacks, and one tackle for loss. Robinson has just 4.5 sacks on the season, but all of them have come since Week 8. Adding to his value, A'Shawn had registered four or more solos in five straight weeks and five or more in three straight coming into Week 14. Tap Robinson as a DT1/DL3 for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Dallas Cowboys.

Kayvon showed up in Week 14, notching two solos, one assist, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Kayvon is up to three sacks on the season but has struggled with health and consistency. He has a neutral matchup against the Baltimore Ravens in Week 15 but is teaming with upside due to the Ravens' recent struggles protecting Lamar Jackson. Add and start THibodeaux as a DL3 option where needed.

Yetur went off in Week 14, racking up four solos, three sacks, and three tackles for loss. Yetur is flourishing with the extra snaps due to Nick Bosa being sidelined and should continue to play a large role for the 49ers' defense, especially on passing downs. Add Yetur where needed as a DL3/4 option for a neutral Week 15 matchup against the Los Angeles Rams.

Chaisson showed up in Week 14, tallying three solos, one assist, 0.5 sacks, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. Chaisson has not done much despite Malcolm Koonce being lost for the season, but has now recorded two full sacks and an interception over his last two games. Still, Chaisson is not a fantasy option outside of 20-team plus 11 v 11 leagues. He is worth a stash in dynasty now that he is showing some signs of life, but should be far from lineups during the fantasy playoffs. Look elsewhere for your Week 15 DL3/4 despite the recent uptick in production.

Broderick is starting to heat up for the Ravens, most recently notching three solos, one sack, and one forced fumble. Washington now has a sack in two of his last three games and can be tapped as a DT2 or DL3/4 for Week 15, thanks to a juicy matchup against the Philadelphia Eagles.

Tershaw Wharton showed up in Week 14, almost matching his season total in sacks with a three solo, two sack, two tackles for loss performance against the Los Angeles Chargers. Wharton is not much of a fantasy option for Week 15 unless you play in three DT leagues. Look elsewhere for Week 15 despite the strong production.

Baun was excellent again in Week 14, tallying six solos, five assists, one sack, and three tackles for loss. Baun has been elite for IDP managers this season and finishes the regular season as the LB1 overall and in fppg. Continue to start Baun as a top-three option for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Pittsburgh Steelers.

Zaire was in his bag in Week 13, tallying 10 solos, two assists, 1.5 sacks, one tackle for loss, one forced fumble, and one pass defended. Zaire is a top two option for Week 15, and he is not number two. Start him with confidence despite the tough on-paper matchup against the Denver Broncos.

Ernest Jones was excellent in Week 14, racking up six solos, two assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Jones has been elite since coming over to the Seahawks and should continue to be deployed as an LB1 option for Week 15 despite the tough on-paper matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Sherwood reasserted himself as an LB1 option in Week 14, exploding for 13 solos, five assists, two tackles for loss, and one pass defended. Jamien had a couple of down weeks that presented some concern, but he responded with his best fantasy output of the season and is now the LB9 in fppg. Tap Sherwood as a LB1 option for a Week 15 matchup against the Jacksonville Jaguars.

Speed was excellent in Week 13, tallying eight solos, one assist, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Speed has turned into a fantasy star in 2023-24 and should continue to be treated as a top-five option for Week 15 despite the tough on-paper matchup against the Denver Broncos.

Henley was solid in Week 14, racking up six solos, two assists, and one pass defended. Henley finishes the regular season as the LB19 in fppg and remains a strong LB2 play for Week 15 despite the tough on-paper matchup against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers. Start Henley everywhere.

Foye was excellent in Week 14, tallying six solos and five assists. The tackle machine remains an elite option but is no longer the unquestioned top option at the position. Fire him up as a top-10 option for Week 15 against Aaron Rodgers and the New York Jets.

Edwards was excellent in Week 14, racking up six solos, four assists, one sack, two tackles for loss, and one pass defended. Edwards has been solid this season but is no longer the LB1 option many drafted him to be. Treat him as an upside LB2 option for Week 15, thanks to a plus matchup against the Miami Dolphins.

Jewell was at it again in Week 14, tallying five solos, five assists, 1.5 sacks, and two tackles for loss. The LB5 in fppg after stringing four consecutive spike weeks together, Jewell is back in the top-15 conversation just in time for the fantasy playoffs and should be added wherever available.

Kendricks was excellent in Week 14, tallying eight solos, four assists, and one tackle for loss. Kendricks has been elite for the Cowboys and should soak up even more tackles with DeMarvion Overshown lost for the season. Fire Kendricks up as an LB1 everywhere.

Elliss was excellent in Week 14, tallying seven solos, three assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Kaden has been one of the most consistent IDP options this season and is an elite LB2 option for Week 15, thanks to a plus matchup against the Las Vegas Raiders on Monday Night Football.

Brooks was excellent in Week 14, racking up four solos, five assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Brooks has been on fire since Week 10 and should be treated as a borderline LB1 option for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Houston Texans. Start Brooks everywhere.

Nakobe was excellent in Week 14, tallying nine solos and three assists. Nakobe has proven his mettle as one of the top IDP options at his position and should continue to be treated as a top-15 play for Week 15, thanks to a plus matchup against the Pittsburgh Steelers. Start Nokobe everywhere.

Quay was at it again in Week 14, tallying six solos, four assists, and one tackle for loss. The LB12 in fppg, Quay should continue to be treated as a top-15 option for Week 15 despite the tough on-paper matchup against the Seattle Seahawks.

Queen was solid in Week 14, tallying five solos, five assists, and one pass defended. Queen has been inconsistent this season and is better deployed as an LB3 as opposed to an LB2, especially with the bye weeks over. Fire Queen up as a top-36 option for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Philadelphia Eagles.

Bolton was excellent in Week 14, racking up five solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Bolton has been far from the elite IDP option many expected him to be, but his most recent spike weeks have cemented him in the LB2 conversation for the fantasy playoffs. Treat him as such for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Cleveland Browns.

Cashman was solid in Week 14, racking up five solos, two assists, and one pass defended. Cashman has been producing at an LB2 level since returning from injury and should be treated as one for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Chicago Bears. Add Cashman where possible.

Lavonte was excellent in Week 14, tallying five solos, two assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one fumble recovery. Lavonte is starting to heat up just in time for the fantasy playoffs but has a neutral at best Week 15 assignment against the Los Angeles Chargers. Treat him as an LB2 option despite the recent uptick in production.

McFadden was excellent in Week 14, exploding for eight solos, three assists, and five tackles for loss. The spike week puts him back in the LB2 conversation just in time for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Baltimore Ravens. Tap him as an LB3 where possible, but squeeze him in as an LB2 if you find yourself in a pinch. Add McFadden wherever available.

Kyzir was solid in Week 14, racking up four solos and nine assists. Kyzir has been a solid LB3 option for most of the season and can be counted as one for a plus Week 15 matchup against the New England Patriots.

ADG was solid in Week 14, notching five solos, four assists, and one pass defended. ADG will continue to see an expanded role for the fantasy playoffs and is someone to plug into lineups as an LB3/4 option for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Tennessee Titans. Start him where needed.

Barton was excellent in Week 13, tallying five solos, three assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Barton has caught fire for the Broncos. Barton is an elite LB2 option for Week 15 despite the tough on-paper matchup against the Indianapolis Colts.

Demario showed up in Week 14, tallying five solos, three assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Demario has been inconsistent this season but has done enough to remain in the LB3/4 conversation for Week 15, thanks to a plus matchup against Washington. Start Demario where needed.

McDuffie has been coming on for the Packers, notching four solos and 11 assists. This was his second spike week in a row, and he should continue to see an expanded role for Week 15, with Edgerrin Cooper expected to be limited even if he does manage to return against the Seattle Seahawks. Fire McDuffie up as an LB3 option despite the tough on-paper matchup. Add McDuffie where needed.

Werner was solid in Week 14, tallying five solos and one assist on 63 percent of the snaps. Werner usually plays north of 80 percent of the snaps, so he could have provided more production if he was closer to the norm against the New York Giants. Werner is locked into his starting role but ceded some snaps to Jordan Howden in three safety looks. Werner is a solid LB3 option for Week 15 thanks to a plus matchup against Washington and has another tasty matchup in Week 17. Add Werner where needed.

Muasau showed up in Week 14, tallying seven solos and one assist. Muasau got the start due to Bobby Okereke (back) being sidelined and could get another start if Okereke can't make it back to the practice field. He is not much of a fantasy option if Okereke is active, so this is a situation to monitor closely. Start Muasau as an LB3/4 option if Okereke is ruled out.

Luke Gifford flashed in Week 14, racking up nine solos, three assists, and one tackle for loss. He drew the start due to the injuries to Kenneth Murray, Jerome Baker, and Jack Gibbens, and with Gibbens done for the year and Murray likely to miss at least another week, Gifford should draw another start. Tap Gifford as an LB3 option if Murray misses time as expected.

Highsmith showed up in Week 14, racking up two solos, one assist, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Highsmith is up to four sacks on the season but has played just seven games due to injury. Highsmith has a plus matchup to take advantage of in Week 15 against the Philadelphia Eagles and should be treated as a DL3 with easy DL2 upside. Add Highsmith everywhere.

Otis Reese flashed in Week 14, racking up four solos, three assists, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. Reese should see an expanded role again this week with Kenneth Murray expected to be sidelined once again, but with Jerome Baker trending towards returning after practicing in full on a Wednesday, it may be Reese and not Luke Gifford who heads back to the bench. Leave Reese on benches or drop him back to the waiver wire altogether for Week 15. Look elsewhere for your LB4/5/flex2.

Budda was excellent in Week 14, tallying eight solos, 10 assists, and one tackle for loss. The DB1 overall and in fppg, Buddha should continue to be treated as a top-three option for a plus Week 15 matchup against the New England Patriots.

Cross was excellent in Week 13, tallying eight solos, one assist, one sack, and one tackle for loss. The DB2 in fppg, Cross is locked in as a top-five option regardless of opponent. Treat him as such for a tasty Week 15 matchup against the Denver Broncos.

Moehrig showed up in Week 14, racking up five solos, three assists, 0.5 sacks, one fumble recovery, and three passes defended. Tre'von had been quiet since Week 9, so it is nice to see him flash before a tasty Week 15 matchup against the Atlanta Falcons. Start Moehrug as a DB3/4 option where needed.

Taylor Rapp popped in Week 14, tallying eight solos and five assists. Rapp has come on strong in the second half of the season, working his way squarely into the DB2 mix even with the bye weeks over. Rapp is a strong DB2 option for Week 15, thanks to a plus matchup against the Detroit Lions. Start Rapp where needed.

Josh Metellus showed up in Week 14, racking up five solos, two assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Metellus has been a disappointment this season, but he is heating up just in time for the fantasy playoffs and can be counted as a DB3 option for Week 15, thanks to a plus matchup against the Chicago Bears.

Amadi was at it again in Week 14, racking up six solos, two assists, and two passes defended. Amadi has become an IDP lynchpin since the Marcus Lattimore trade, not only achieving CB1 status but forcing his way into the legit DB2 conversation. Treat Amadi as a top-25 option for Week 15, thanks to a tasty matchup against the New York Giants.

Hamlin showed up in Week 14, tallying seven solos and six assists against the Los Angeles Rams. It was his first spike week since Week 9, but Hamlin was excellent in the first half of the season. Hopefully, this is the start of another tear. Add and start Hamlin as an upside DB3 option for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Detroit Lions.

Peppers was solid in his return from the exempt list, tallying five solos, four assists, and one tackle for loss. Peppers immediately stepped back into a starting role and could be an impact player down the stretch for fantasy managers in deeper leagues. Treat him as a DB3 for Week 15 despite a tough on-paper matchup against the Arizona Cardinals.

Blackmon was excellent in Week 13, racking up five solos, one interception, and one pass defended against the New England Patriots. Blackmon has had his share of spike weeks but has not lived up to expectations, especially after a Week 1 explosion seemed to validate hopes of a breakout. Still, Blackmon is a strong DB2/3 option and should be tapped as a DB2 for Week 15, thanks to a plus matchup against the Denver Broncos.

Owens continues to flash when called upon, this time recording five solos, two assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Owens has seen an expanded role with Elijah Hicks (ankle) sidelined and is expected to draw another start for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Minnesota Vikings on Monday Night Football. Add Owens where possible as a DB3 with DB2 upside.

Donovan Wilson showed up again in Week 14, tallying five solos, four assists, 0.5 sacks, and one forced fumble. Wilson has been a massive disappointment this season and should be left on benches for the fantasy quarterfinals despite starting to heat up. There are no more byes, so there is no need to roll with such a low-floor option outside of 20-team leagues. Keep Wilson glued to benches for Week 15 for a tough on-paper matchup against the Carolina Panthers.

CJGJ showed up in Week 14, racking up three solos, three assists, one interception, and two passes defended. CJGJ has been a boom-or-bust play this season, relegating him to DB3 status despite his immense talent. With that said, he has an excellent playoff schedule starting with the Pittsburgh Steelers this week. Add and start Gardner-Johnson as an upside DB3 for the plus matchup.

Geno showed up in Week 14, racking up three solos, two assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Geno has been a boom-or-bust option this season and hasn't come close to living up to the expectations thrust upon him after starring in a backup role to Kyle Hamilton and Marcus Williams while with the Ravens. Geno has upside but should be left on benches where possible for Week 15 despite the plus matchup against the Tennesee Titans. Look elsewhere for your DB3.

Kaevon was excellent in Week 14, racking up four solos, three assists, and one sack on 82 percent of the snaps. The Buccaneers are dealing with injuries to both of their starting safeties, so Kaevon should get all the run he can handle down the stretch. Merriweather projects as a strong DB3 option and is someone those in the deeper leagues will want to give consideration to as a DB3/4 option who may still be floating on your waiver wire. Start Kaevon where needed.

Chamarri was at it again in Week 14, notching seven solos, two assists, and one tackle for loss. Conner has been an IDP force out of the slot and should continue to be treated as an upside DB3 option for a plus Week 15 matchup against the Cleveland Browns. Add and start Chamarri everywhere.
